<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-462-532  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 462 532.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Networking Management  July 1989 v7 n7 p44(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Protecting the network from AC power problems. (includes relatedarticles entitled 'common ac problems' and 'LAN susceptibility topower failure')</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rhodes, Bruce.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Communications managers have been forced to take a hard look attheir ac power with the increased use of sophisticated electronicequipment within the telecom industry during the 1980s.andP;  Utilitiesare required by law to provide voltage within plus-or-minus 10percent of the nominal 120 or 220 volts, but some electronicsystems are not designed to handle such irregular fluctuations.andO;The problems are multiplied with data networks, because the wholesystem can crash if one component suffers a power-related problem.andO;There are three kinds of power protection products: those thatprovide power conditioning of incoming ac power, those that supplyback-up emergency battery power, and those that do both.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Power SupplyVoltage RegulatorsBack-Up Power SupplyUninterruptible Power SupplyAlternating Current.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Basic UPS functionality. (chart)Latest generation of UPS. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>